Based on a backward‐induction analysis for this alternating‐offer game (with 12 rounds) – where in every round Bob’s dollars lose a further 20% of their value while Alice’s value stays constant – the (subgame perfect) equilibrium outcome in round 1 is for Alice to propose that she gets 737,856 dollars and Bob gets 262,144 dollars (which sum to 1,000,000). In equilibrium Bob is exactly indifferent between accepting this offer in round 1 (getting 262,144 dollars at full value) and waiting one round so that by his own discounting his eventual gain would be worth the same in today’s dollars.

